Kd1 Qb7 16. Qh5+ Kd8 17. Qe2 Qxb6 18. Nc3 Bxc4 19. Qxc4 $14) 9. fxe3 Qg4 (9...
Na6 $6 10. d4 axb4 11. O-O $16) 10. b5 $1 Qxg2 (10... e4 $6 11. Nd4 Qxg2 12.
Rf1 Bxc5 13. Ba3 $1 Bxa3 14. Qxa3 Qxh2 15. Nc3 $16) 11. Rf1 Bxc5 12. Bxg8 Rxg8
13. Qc4 {A double attack, which does not put an end of the game, for the
position is full of various tricks.} Rf8 14. Rf2 $1 (14. Qxc5 {is not clear at
all because of} Bh3 $1 15. Rf2 Qh1+ 16. Ke2 Nd7 17. Qc2 Bg4 $44) 14... Qh1+ 15.
Ke2 (15. Rf1 $11) 15... cxb5 16. Qxc5 (16. Qxb5+ Nc6) 16... Na6 17. Qxb5+ Bd7
18. Qxb7 Rb8 19. Qxa6 Qxc1 20. Rf1 Qxf1+ 21. Kxf1 Bb5+ 22. Qxb5+ Rxb5 23. Nc3
Rb2 24. Ke2 $14 {Murray - D'Adamo, ICCF email, 2017, though Black has managed
to hold.}) 7. b5 Bxc5 8. Bc4 Ne7 {Preventing the direct threat 9.Bxg8, Black
can also consider:} (8... dxe3 9. fxe3 e4 10. Nd4 Bxd4 11. exd4 Ne7 12. Nc3 $36
) (8... Qe7 9. O-O dxe3 10. fxe3 Be6 11. Bxe6 Qxe6 12. Qe4 Ne7 13. Qxb7 Qd5 14.
Qxc7 Bd6 15. Qc2 Qxb5 16. Nc3 Qc4 17. Qe4 Qxe4 18. Nxe4 Nc8 19. Rb1 $14) (8...
Bb6 $146 9. exd4 (9. O-O Bg4) 9... Bg4 10. O-O Bxf3 11. Qb3 $1 Qxd4 12. Bxg8
Bh5 13. Bb2 ({if} 13. Ba3 {, then} Kd8 $1 {is a remarkable way to disable the
devastating queen penetration on e6 - now, without giving a check, it can lead
only to a draw, for instance} 14. Nc3 a4 15. Qe6 Qd7 16. Qc4 Qd4 $11) 13... Qb4
14. Qe6+ Qe7 15. Qc8+ Qd8 16. Qh3 $5 (16. Qe6+ $11) 16... Bg6 17. Nc3 Nd7 (
17... Rxg8 $2 18. Qe6+) 18. Na4 (18. Bd5 $5 Nc5 19. Qf3 Qd7 20. d4 Ne6 21. Na4
O-O) 18... Nc5 19. Nxc5 Bxc5 20. Rac1 Bb4 21. Bc4 Qd7 22. Qb3 {With his Ke8
still in the center Black has to tread very carefully -} Qe7 23. b6 $1 cxb6 24.
d4 O-O-O 25. a3 Bd6 26. Qxb6 Kb8 27. dxe5 (27. Rfe1 Qc7) 27... Bxe5 28. Rfe1
Rc8 29. Bxe5+ fxe5 30. Bd5 $44) 9. exd4 exd4 10. Ba3 Bxa3 $1 (10... b6 $6 11.
Bxc5 bxc5 12. O-O $40) (10... Na6 {is the old main line, when critical is} 11.
O-O Nb4 12. Re1 {and Black is definitely in a need for good advice:} Bg4 $1 {
is relatively the best -} (12... c6 $6 {is spectacularly met by the temporary
piece sacrifice} 13. Nc3 $1 dxc3 14. dxc3 {and White's considerable lead in
development can quickly tell, for instance} Bxf2+ 15. Kxf2 cxb5 16. Bxb5 Qb6+
17. Nd4 Bxb5 18. Qxb5+ Qxb5 19. Nxb5 Nd3+ 20. Kf1 Nxe1 21. Rxe1 $16) ({no
wonder that} 12... b6 $6 {is running into the same} 13. Nc3 $1 dxc3 ({one move
later} 13... c6 {does not solve the opening problems either , as shown by} 14.
Ne4 cxb5 15. Bxb5 Bxb5 16. Qxb5+ Qd7 17. Qc4 $16 {and Ke8 is still stuck in
the center}) 14. dxc3 Nc2 $5 15. Qxc2 {(now it is a real piece sacrifice)} Bxa3
16. Qb3 Bd6 17. Bg8 $3 {(not an average move, is it?)} Bg4 18. Nd4 Rxg8 19.
Qxg8+ Kd7 20. Rxe7+ $1 (20. Qxg7 $2 Qg8 21. Qxf6 Nd5 $13) 20... Bxe7 21. Qc4 $1
{One more tactical subtlety, after which White regains the piece with interest
-} Kc8 22. Nc6 Qd7 23. Qe4 f5 24. Nxe7+ Kb8 25. Nc6+ Kc8 26. Qe3 Kb7 27. Re1
$16) (12... Kf8 $6 13. Nc3 $16) (12... Bf5 13. Nh4 Kf8 14. Qd1 {[%cal Gd1f3]}
g6 15. Qf3 Kg7 16. Nc3 Rf8 17. Rac1 $36) 13. d3 $1 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Kf8 15. Nd2 {
and now:} Ned5 {is the safer way to centralize this knight -} (15... Ng6 $6 16.
Ne4 Be7 (16... b6 17. f4 Nh4 18. Qd1 g6 19. Nxc5 bxc5 20. Qg4 Nf5 21. Re2 Kg7
22. Rae1 $14) 17. Ng3 $1 Ne5 {completes the intended knight manoeuvre, but
here White has a sound exchange sacrifice at his disposal -} 18. Rxe5 $1 fxe5
19. Re1 g6 20. Rxe5 Kg7 {The king has ran out of the dangerous central zone,
